body:
Our current solution for "configurable constants" is to edit a file as a precompilation step. See #220.
A more full-featured solution would be to create a `BeaconConfig` object that would store tweaked "constants", ssz types, and misc other things (eg: a logger). (See https://github.com/ChainSafe/lodestar/pull/220#issuecomment-494942476 for more context)

It could look something like:
```typescript
interface Constants {
  SHARD_COUNT: number;
  // ... the rest of the configurable constants
}

interface SSZTypes {
  Fork: AnySSZType;
  // ... the rest of the ssz types
}

interface BeaconConfig {
  constants: Constants;
  ssz: SSZTypes;
  logger: AbstractLogger;
}
```
Then we can pass around the BeaconConfig (created in cli startup or BeaconNode constructor) throughout the project, even down to the more functional bits:
```typescript
// pass in a BeaconConfig to the state transition helpers
executeStateTransition(state, block, config);

// and pass in a config to any functions that use constants, ssz types, need logging, etc.
export function getShardDelta(state: BeaconState, epoch: Epoch, c: BeaconConfig): number {
  return Math.min(
    getEpochCommitteeCount(state, epoch, c),
    c.constants.SHARD_COUNT - intDiv(c.constants.SHARD_COUNT, c.constants.SLOTS_PER_EPOCH),
  );
}
```

I agree most of the time constants would be changed before run-time, unfortunately, we can't really expose "compile-time" to end users, we only publish transpiled javascript, so we only have run-time to handle changing the constants. This is one of the major issues with our current file-based approach.

Ultimately, I think its a pretty subjective call. Are these variables actual constants? or are they runtime parameters?
If they're constants, they should just be imported and used as implicit parameters.
If they're runtime parameters, they should be passed in as parameters explicitly.

My current thought is that we should treat many of the constants as runtime parameters, even if mainnet will only use one specific definition of them, with definitions known well ahead of time.
We'll be doing enough testing that non-mainnet configurations will be an important "first-class" usecase.

Realistically, we won't need to add a BeaconConfig to every function everywhere, just functions that require these runtime parameters (mainly top-level modules and a bunch of state transition functions).

Perhaps in the purely functional sections, we can add the config as the first parameter, rather than the last, to avoid issues with defaults.

I'm hopeful we can avoid most of the boilerplate in tests:
```typescript
const conf1: ChainConfig = getMainnetConfig();
expect(funcTested(conf1, arg1)).to.be.foo()
// or
const conf2: ChainConfig = getMinimalConfig();
expect(funcTested(conf2, arg1)).to.be.bar()

// which isn't much different than the ergonomics of a singleton approach
setChainConfig(mainnet);
expect(funcTested(arg1)).to.be.foo();
// or
setChainConfig(minimal);
expect(funcTested(arg1)).to.be.bar();
```

Yeah but we can expose config as singleton and therefore every constant will be runtime params. It's javascript so we basically have only runtime params because we can override any export to suit our need which I'm abusing in unit tests. I think the issue we are trying to figure out whether to inject config by importing it or pass it by reference throughout application. I'm leaning towards first as it doesn't require tectonic changes on code and tests and reduces boilerplate code of passing config object reference down the method call chain.

```javascript
import *  as mainet from './constants/mainet';
import * as minimal from './constant/minimal';

class BeaconConfig {
   public SLOT_PER_EPOCH: number;
   
   constructor() {
      this.applyMainet();
   }

   public function applyMainnet() {
      //set properties from mainet
   }

   public function applyMinimal() {
   }

   public function applyCustom(constants);
  
}

export default new BeaconConfig();
```

And in every file:
```javascript
import config from '/config';

config.applyMinimal();
config.SLOTS_PER_EPOCH;
```

I definitely see how its a lot less of a code change, and how it could work.

My main concern is more that singletons are process-wide, whereas injected dependencies are only instance-wide.
Singletons are configured by a series of side-effects, whereas injected dependencies are configured by creating a new dependency via constructor or function.
I think dependency injection is just a conceptually cleaner way to build up a big project like this and in this case worth the additional parameterization. Hiding the chain config in a singleton is easy to implement, but it couples everything in a subtle way that I don't think is the best.

Eg: Should a `BeaconConfig` apply to all running `BeaconNode`s? or is the Config unique to the Node that's running?
```typescript
// compare 6 second block time to 2 second block time
config.applyMainnet();
const nodeA = new BeaconNode();
config.applyMinimal();
const nodeB = new BeaconNode();
nodeA.start();
nodeB.start();
// unfortunately, now nodeA and nodeB both follow the minimal config
```
I don't actually think (m)any people will be running multiple beacon nodes with different configs, but this highlights a bit of the reasoning.
I think the config is a product of the running beacon node, rather than a product of the environment in which its running. Using a singleton makes the config a product of the environment.
